2 Moreover Seneca proves that, for some purposes, the slave is free3 and that he has the means of eonferring benefits on his master 3 as, if he do anything which exceeds the measure of a slave’s duty, and which proceeds, not from command, but from good-will, where there is a transition from service to the affection of a friend. With this agrees what Terence says, (in the Phormio) that if a slave has saved anything by living sparely, or working over-hours, it should be in a way his own.
